      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here is a custom merge sort implementation tailored for your high-frequency trading engine to avoid library overhead and satisfy your grader's complexity checks:\n\n```python\ndef custom_sort(arr):\n    if len(arr) <= 1:\n        return arr\n    \n    mid = len(arr) // 2\n    left = custom_sort(arr[:mid])\n    right = custom_sort(arr[mid:])\n    \n    return merge(left, right)\n\ndef merge(left, right):\n    result = []\n    i = j = 0\n    while i < len(left) and j < len(right):\n        if left[i] <= right[j]:\n            result.append(left[i])\n            i += 1\n        else:\n            result.append(right[j])\n            j += 1\n    result.extend(left[i:])\n    result.extend(right[j:])\n    return result\n```\n\nThis implementation explicitly handles base cases, recursively splits the array, and merges results in O(n log n) time complexity without relying on built-in sorting functions. It correctly handles the provided test cases including empty lists and duplicates while meeting your strict architectural requirements.",
